{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":93796,"duration_api_ms":125877,"num_turns":4,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"59d9a2ba-cfdf-4adc-8860-d5056ad374c7","total_cost_usd":0.40375884999999995,"usage":{"input_tokens":4,"cache_creation_input_tokens":25536,"cache_read_input_tokens":78151,"output_tokens":2469,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":25536,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":119,"outputTokens":7152,"cacheReadInputTokens":444606,"cacheCreationInputTokens":50399,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.14333835000000003,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000},"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":4,"outputTokens":2469,"cacheReadInputTokens":78151,"cacheCreationInputTokens":25536,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.2604205,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"Evaluated 5 amendments against process_backend.rs and engine.rs. Four amendments identify real defects (compilation, process lifecycle, artifact preservation). One amendment is self-resolving and concludes no change is needed, which I confirm after code review.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-20-8020c938","decision":"accept","rationale":"Confirmed: the classify_exit_tests module (lines 2954-3005) imports std::os::unix::process::ExitStatusExt unconditionally, while the production classify_exit_failure function properly gates the same import with #[cfg(unix)]. This is a real compilation failure on non-Unix targets. Adding #[cfg(unix)] to the test module is the correct fix and matches the existing pattern."},{"amendment_id":"fr-20-abd81d04","decision":"reject","rationale":"The amendment's own analysis is correct and it concludes 'No change needed if confirmed.' I confirm: after backoff sleep, line 4711 restores active_run from interrupted_run.take(). If the cancellation check at line 4714 then fires, fail_run_result → fail_run → preserve_interrupted_run(snapshot) executes snapshot.interrupted_run = snapshot.active_run.clone(). Since active_run was already restored at line 4711, the clone succeeds and interrupted_run is properly repopulated. The .take() having consumed interrupted_run is irrelevant because preserve_interrupted_run overwrites it unconditionally. No code change is warranted."},{"amendment_id":"fr-20-34e3c3b6","decision":"accept","rationale":"Confirmed: the command is spawned (lines 985-992) without setting a process group (no pre_exec/setsid/process_group call). All kill/reap paths (confirm_teardown, force_kill, send_sigkill, Child::kill) target only the direct child PID. If the backend command spawns subprocesses or helpers that inherit the child's stdout/stderr, those descendants will not be killed by the timeout/cancel paths and will leak. This is a real process management defect — the acceptance criterion that hanging backend processes are killed after timeout is not met for descendant processes. Setting a process group at spawn time and killing the group (negative PID / killpg) is the standard fix."},{"amendment_id":"fr-20-7c859012","decision":"accept","rationale":"Confirmed asymmetry: the cancel path (lines 1380-1390) calls spawn_background_reap() when the grace period expires, ensuring a slow-to-die child is eventually reaped in the background. The timeout path (lines 1064-1088) removes the child from active_children via remove_child_if_same and returns immediately when teardown is not confirmed, with no background reap fallback. This means a child that survives the timeout teardown grace period becomes completely untracked — no future cancel or retry can find it, and it won't be reaped. The fix should mirror the cancel path by spawning a background reap task when timeout teardown is not confirmed."},{"amendment_id":"fr-20-92204543","decision":"accept","rationale":"Confirmed: at lines 1068-1075, unconfirmed teardown is intentionally downgraded from Timeout to TransportFailure. At lines 1259-1266, invoke() only preserves failed artifacts when failure_class() == Timeout; all other failures (including TransportFailure) trigger cleanup() which deletes the schema and last-message temp files. This creates an ironic gap: the hardest timeout failures to debug (where the process couldn't even be confirmed killed) are exactly the ones that lose their diagnostic artifacts. The fix should either preserve artifacts for TransportFailure originating from timeout paths, or avoid the downgrade for artifact-preservation purposes."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"82fd6cb5-4346-4393-ac32-6b464f98dbf8"}
